THE RISK:
{
 "id": "stock-flow-geo-misprice",
 "title": "The geo split is a museum exhibit: NL's 0.28 is installed stock, but Year-1 revenue lives in the flow — which the Dutch hyperscale ban has already redirected",
 "narrative": "Every geo ratio is derived from a 2025 installed-colocation snapshot. But a pre-launch entrant sells into new fit-outs and expansions — the flow — and the flow map looks nothing like the stock map. Since early 2024 the Netherlands bans new hyperscale data centres outside two municipalities, Amsterdam's connections are capped, and even the DC Byte commentary notes development activity has structurally slowed with 'other markets offering strong alternatives.' Meanwhile investment is shifting to regional hubs and eastward. Weighting Year-1 sales coverage, certification sequencing, and channel hires by a 0.28 NL share systematically points the venture at the geography where the least new PDU-consuming capacity will be commissioned during its window.",
 "category": "model-structure",
 "targetNodes": [
  "geo.NL",
  "geo.PL",
  "geo.other"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "An amended decree bans new hyperscale data centres (70+ MW) in the Netherlands outside Het Hogeland and Hollands Kroon since early 2024, and Amsterdam's draft zoning plan caps new connections at 350 MVA until 2030 — the NL new-build flow is administratively foreclosed, not merely slow",
   "refs": [
    "digest:geo-NL#c7",
    "digest:geo-NL#c8"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Cushman & Wakefield reports Amsterdam at 852 MW with 'less room for further expansion, while investment is more quickly shifting to other European hubs and to regional locations'; DC Byte notes post-moratorium development runs at a reduced rate — so CE fit-out flow reallocates toward Germany, Poland and the CEE tail while NL's installed stock keeps its 28% weight in the model",
   "refs": [
    "digest:geo-NL#c0",
    "digest:geo-NL#c16",
    "ledger:geo.NL"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "For a first-12-months entrant, PDU demand is proportional to commissioned/expanded capacity in the window, not to standing stock; geo.NL's 0.28 overstates the NL slice of orderable demand while geo.PL (0.07) and geo.other (0.03) — where the derivations already flag divergent, faster-growing scopes — understate theirs",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:geo.PL",
    "ledger:geo.other",
    "profile:Stage"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The NL node looks like the model's safest: triangulated, two sources agreeing within 3%. That agreement is precisely the trap — both sources measure the same stock quantity, and stock is the wrong quantity for a Year-1 revenue model. A number can be perfectly sourced and still be the answer to a different question.",
 "expectedObviousness": "low",
 "falsifier": "DDA's 2026 State of the Dutch Data Centers (or Statista's 2026 update) showing NL colocation MW additions at or above 28% of total CE-7 additions for the year.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.62,
  "rationale": "The hyperscale ban, the Amsterdam connection cap, and C&W's explicit 'investment shifting' statement are all in force today; the uncertainty is magnitude (retrofit and the two exempt municipalities keep some NL flow alive), not direction. [evidence revision: The ban's legal force and the flow-reallocation direction are strongly and independently corroborated, and DDA 2026 shows NL growth (7%/12% CAGR) trailing the European average — consistent with the falsifier not being met. Modest upward revision from 0.55; magnitude uncertainty remains because the two exempt municipalities, regional NL hubs (Groningen/South Holland/North Brabant), and retrofit still keep meaningful NL colocation flow alive, and precise NL-vs-CE-7 additions shares were not quantified in the results.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.55
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "geo.NL",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.18,
   "note": "NL flow share well below its stock share given the ban and connection cap"
  },
  {
   "nodeId": "geo.PL",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.11,
   "note": "Poland absorbs a larger share of window-period additions"
  },
  {
   "nodeId": "geo.other",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.05,
   "note": "CEE tail (esp. Romania) takes redirected flow; net effect is a modest TAM haircut plus a mix shift"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "NL colocation capacity additions vs CE-7 additions",
   "where": "Dutch Data Center Association annual State of the Dutch Data Centers report",
   "threshold": "NL additions <15% of CE-7 additions in 2026",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Exemption-zone activity (Eemshaven, Agriport) vs rest-of-NL permitting",
   "where": "Het Hogeland / Hollands Kroon municipal permit registers; DC Byte Amsterdam market updates",
   "threshold": "No new non-exempt NL hyperscale permits granted in 2026",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Poland/CEE commissioning announcements",
   "where": "PMR Poland data-center market updates; Atman/Data4/Vantage Warsaw press releases",
   "threshold": "≥100 MW of new CE-east commissionings announced for 2026–27",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Rebuild the geography weights on a 2026–27 additions basis (announced commissioning MW per country) instead of installed stock, and re-run the funnel",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "geo.NL",
   "note": "One analyst-week using DC Byte/C&W pipeline data; directly re-prices the NL/PL/CEE mix"
  },
  {
   "action": "Sequence go-to-market coverage Frankfurt-first, Warsaw-second, and treat NL as a retrofit-only territory in Year 1",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Aligns scarce launch resources with where PDUs will actually be ordered in the window"
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "Challenges in the Dutch Data Center Market",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Greenberg Traurig LLP",
   "date": "2024-03",
   "excerpt": "an amendment of the decree...that entered into force on 1 January 2024, no hyperscale data centers are [permitted]",
   "url": "https://www.gtlaw.com/en/insights/2024/3/challenges-in-the-dutch-data-center-market",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "DDA: stroomvoorziening bepaalt tempo Nederlandse datacentergroei",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "MSP Business (citing DDA State of the Dutch Data Centers 2026)",
   "date": "2026-06-08",
   "excerpt": "Tot 2031 verwacht de DDA een gemiddelde jaarlijkse groei van twaalf procent, naar 2,8 gigawatt. Die groei blijft desondanks achter bij het Europese gemiddelde.",
   "url": "https://mspbusiness.com/markt-en-strategie/dda-stroomvoorziening-bepaalt-tempo-nederlandse-datacentergroei/",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Why Flexibility Has Become Key to Success in EMEA Data Centre Markets",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "DC Byte",
   "date": "2026-06-04",
   "excerpt": "Pipeline across major markets has slowed down...The major beneficiaries of this shift have been emerging markets, such as the Nordics, Southern Europe and the Middle East",
   "url": "https://www.dcbyte.com/news-blogs/why-flexibility-has-become-key-to-success-in-emea-data-centre-markets/",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://www.gtlaw.com/en/insights/2024/3/challenges-in-the-dutch-data-center-market",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Further to an amendment of the decree concerning rules on the quality of the physical environment and the performance of tasks and authorities (Besluit kwaliteit leefomgeving) that entered into force on 1 January 2024, no hyperscale data centers are"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://zoek.officielebekendmakingen.nl/stcrt-2023-35432.html",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "deze instructieregels bepalen dat een omgevingsplan geen hyperscale datacentra toelaat"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.dcbyte.com/news-blogs/why-flexibility-has-become-key-to-success-in-emea-data-centre-markets/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "London, Frankfurt, Amsterdam and Paris remain important centres, particularly for finance and enterprise demand, but aren’t growing at the rate they once were due to constraints on land and power. The major beneficiaries of this shift have been emerging markets"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.bakermckenzie.com/en/newsroom/2025/07/data-centers-in-poland-attract-investor-interest",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "due to problems with energy supply, restrictions on the development of data centers have been introduced in Europe by countries such as the Netherlands, France and Ireland"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.dutchdatacenters.nl/en/nieuws/ten-years-of-state-of-the-dutch-data-centers-a-decade-of-growth-and-challenges/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "While the Amsterdam Metropolitan Area (MRA) still accounts for approximately 70% of colocation capacity, growth is shifting toward regions such as Groningen, South Holland, and North Brabant"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://mspbusiness.com/markt-en-strategie/dda-stroomvoorziening-bepaalt-tempo-nederlandse-datacentergroei/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Eind 2025 bereikte de Nederlandse markt ruim 1,5 gigawatt aan IT-vermogen, een stijging van zeven procent ten opzichte van het jaar daarvoor. Tot 2031 verwacht de DDA een gemiddelde jaarlijkse groei van twaalf procent, naar 2,8 gigawatt. Die groei blijft desondanks achter bij het Europese gemiddelde."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.rabobank.com/knowledge/d011517320-data-center-growth-in-europe-expands-to-emerging-markets",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Grid congestion, land limitations, and planning restrictions increasingly constrain the expansion of established core data center hubs. As a result, new developments are gradually emerging in alternative markets in Europe."
  }
 ]
}

